The second Global COVID-19 Summit, co-hosted by the United States, Belize, Germany, Indonesia, and Senegal, focused on accelerating efforts to vaccinate people, improve access to tests and treatments, protect healthcare workers, and finance future pandemic preparedness. The Summit resulted in new financial commitments totaling $3.2 billion, including $2.5 billion for COVID-19 response activities and $712 million for a new pandemic preparedness and global health security fund at the World Bank. Over 50 organizations, including NGOs, businesses, philanthropies, and advocacy groups, made commitments totaling over $700 million towards vaccinating the world and enhancing health security. These commitments are in addition to the funds already pledged in 2022.